¶ ⦊
  ‖ ‹Factorial function.› ⦉

  ‖ Define $f: 𝗡 → 𝗡$ recursively by $f(1) = 1$ and $f(2) =
    2f(1)$, and $f(n) = nf(n-1)$ for $n ∈ 𝗡$ ($f$ exists by
    the the recursion theorem—see␣
    <a href='/sheets/recursion_theorem.html'>
      ‖ Recursion Theorem ⦉
    </a>
    ). ⦉

  ‖ $f$ is defined such that $f(n)$ is $n$ factorial, for which
    reason we call $f$ the ❬factorial function❭. ⦉

  ‖ For convenience, we extend $f$ to $ω$
    † ⦊
      ‖ See␣
        <a href='/sheets/natural_numbers.html#Notation'>
          ‖ Natural Numbers ⦉
        </a>
        . ⦉
    ⦉
    by defining $f(0) = 1$. ⦉
⦉

§§ Notation ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We denote the factorial of $n$ by $n!$, read aloud “n
    factorial”. ⦉

  ‖ So for example, $5! = 5·4·3·2·1$ and $0! = 1$. ⦉
⦉

